WT-TG Quality Control

1. Introduction

This document describes the seurat quality control analysis. The data is filtered based on quality analysis. The quality of the data is visualized before and after filtering.

#Install and load required R packages. Install the packages if you do not already have them installed
library(Seurat)
library(kableExtra)
library(ggplot2)
library(plotly)
library(tidyverse)
library(rmarkdown)
# Project name
project_name = "scRNA-Seq Nilisha"
# Input path
datadirectory <- "/Users/nagarajanv/OneDrive - National Institutes of Health/Working/scRNAseqNilisha/"
# Set working directory
setwd(datadirectory)
# Set sample groups
samples <- c("WT","TG")

2. Combined cellranger count metrics

The below table shows the cellranger metrics for the generated counts. The table is also saved in the file Cellranger_Metrics_combined.txt

########### Combine cellranger metrics data
sample_metrics <- lapply(samples, function(i){
  metrics <- read.csv(paste0(i,"_metrics_summary.csv",sep=""), colClasses = "character")
})
# Combine sample metrics
sample_metrics <- do.call("rbind", sample_metrics)
#View(sample_metrics)
# Assign rownames with sample names
rownames(sample_metrics) <- samples
# Extract metrics data
sample_metrics <- data.frame(t(sample_metrics[,c(4:17,1,18,2,3,19,20)]))
# Format rows and columns
row.names(sample_metrics) <- gsub("\\."," ", rownames(sample_metrics))
sample_metrics$Name<-rownames(sample_metrics)
sample_metrics<-sample_metrics[,c(ncol(sample_metrics),1:(ncol(sample_metrics)-1))]
# Save the combined metrics as a tab delimited text file
write.table(sample_metrics, file="Cellranger_Metrics_combined.txt", quote=F, row.names = FALSE, sep = "\t")
# Display the table
paged_table(sample_metrics)

4. Combine datasets

# min.cells - include features detected in atleast this many cells
# min.features - include cells where atleast this many features are detected
# names.field - will set WT, TG as initial identity
# Create seurat objects
WT_gex_s <- CreateSeuratObject(WT_gex,project = "Gex",min.cells = 0,min.features = 300,names.field = 2,names.delim = "\\-")

# Generate violin plot for before filtering
set.seed(12345)
#nFeature_RNA is number of genes in a cell
#nCount_RNA is number of reads/transcripts/molecules in a cell
table(WT_TG$orig.ident)
## 
##   TG   WT 
## 2850 2479
qcbefore=VlnPlot(WT_TG,features = c("nFeature_RNA", "nCount_RNA","percent.mito","percent.ribo"),ncol = 2, pt.size = 0.2) + NoLegend()
qcbefore

# Save the plot in current working directory
ggsave("qcbefore-violineplot.png", plot = qcbefore, width = 15, height = 20, units = "cm")

7. Quality control (Filtering)

# Filter cells
# Counts before filtering
table(WT_TG$orig.ident)
## 
##   TG   WT 
## 2850 2479
WT_TG_Filt <- subset(WT_TG, percent.mito <= 8)
# Counts after mito filtering
table(WT_TG_Filt$orig.ident)
## 
##   TG   WT 
## 2693 2364
WT_TG_Filt <- subset(WT_TG_Filt, nCount_RNA >= 3000 & nCount_RNA <= 15000)
# Counts after ncount filtering
table(WT_TG_Filt$orig.ident)
## 
##   TG   WT 
## 1518 1042
WT_TG_Filt <- subset(WT_TG_Filt, nFeature_RNA >= 700 & nFeature_RNA < 3000)
# Counts after all filtering
table(WT_TG_Filt$orig.ident)
## 
##   TG   WT 
## 1060  781
# Generate violin plot for after filtering
qcafter=VlnPlot(WT_TG_Filt,features = c("nFeature_RNA", "nCount_RNA","percent.mito","percent.ribo"),ncol = 2, pt.size = 0.1) +
  NoLegend()
qcafter

# Save the plots
ggsave("qcafter-violineplot.png", plot = qcafter, width = 15, height = 20, units = "cm")
# Save QC session data in the working directory
save.image(file='SeuratObjectAfterQc.RData')
